However, when GO reacts with the ·OH radicals, the carbon atoms connected with hydroxyl and epoxide are attacked by these powerful oxidizing agents, breaking either carbon single bonds (CC) or double bonds (CC) and then the new groups containing oxygen serve as new reaction sites, thus forming small localized groups. Fig. 3
                     a shows the reaction mechanism for GOOP and GOGP, where excess ·OH radicals from H2O2 facilitate the deprotonation of carbon atoms [39]. One of the secondary reactions leads to the formation of water molecules and the formation of vacancies on the surface of the CMG sheets. Moreover, thermally formed defects in the GO serve as binding sites for chemisorption and radical formation, especially hydroxyl radicals from thermally dissociated water. The spread and release of CO and CO2 is a result of a thermally induced oxidative disruption in the GO network, leading to random locations of functional groups in the material. Nevertheless, CO is a strong reducing agent, therefore it is possible that CO2 production is given by a repetitive process due to temperature increase. This process is also involved in exfoliation and shrinkage of CMG sheets where atomic oxygen can be transformed to O2 from reactions with the radical ·OH and secondary reactions with H2O2. Therefore, ·OH radicals are more predisposed to react with CO to form CO2 and COOH radicals by increasing the temperature of the medium [43]. Through IR spectrophotometry (Fig. 3b) the frequencies characterizing the functional groups ether (CO), alkene (CC), carbonyl (CO
                     ), formyl (HCO) were detected, whereas carboxylic acid (COOH) and water (H2O) formed in the GOOP material (green spectrum) differ from the GOGP solution (orange spectrum), the latter only presenting defined signals of alkene functional groups (ν ˜ 1620 cm−1), hydroxyl and formyl radicals (ν ˜ 800 - 3700 cm−1). Furthermore, the orange spectrum of the GOOP material confirms that the oxygenated groups are bind to the carbon atoms, showing the signal of the CO and CO groups. After the hydrothermal treatment they are convert into CO and CO2 maintained the signal of the CC bonds on graphene oxide. On the other hand, the GOGP spectrum does not show the signal from the ether group due this material underwent a longer hydrothermal process than GOOP, where the temperature and the ·OH radicals acted over CC bonds. Hence, the CC bonds be kept, leading to CMG sheets have a good dispersion and stability in the solvent. The temperatures used for the synthesis show that below 200 °C hydroxyl radicals are not completely converted to CO2 with possible contributions from COOH and HCO radicals. According Acik et al. [43], at 200 °C, radicals attack CO (acting as a scavenger for hydroxyl radicals), forming a maximum for the CO2 production. The functional groups embedded in GO particles cause them to convert to photoluminescent particles showing different light emissions when excited with a light source of λ = 375 nm due to the photogeneration of the e – h + pair by absorbing light in the highest orbitals of organic molecules (links CC da π - π*) generating a transition period of e- through the different bands of the LUMO until it falls to HOMO emitting a photon with different energy to that absorbed until the electrical charges in the GO are balanced. These are created by the stable formation of CO and C–O groups in the aromatic structure of the GO giving rise to an optical bandwidth (Eg). The photoluminescent properties of the material are attributed to the heterogeneous electronic structure of the GO by the presence of the agglomeration of carbon atoms with sp2 hybridization [44]. The emission spectrum of GOOP (Fig. 3, orange line) has an emission maximum at λ≈ 634 nm. This is due to electronic transitions of π → π* (λ = 230 nm) and n → π* (λ = 320 nm) from the CO. Also, the orange PL is attributed to the GO with GN−COO-* ions which is formed from the ionic groups (−COO-) coming from the deprotonation of the carboxylic acid groups in the basal state and reprotoned in the state of electronic excitation [45].
